    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Sport played with two teams of 11 players on an oblong ball on a rectangular field marked by vertical yard lines called a "gridiron." It evolved from English rugby and soccer (association football); it differs from soccer chiefly in allowing players to touch, throw, and carry the ball with their hands, and it differs from rugby in allowing each side to control the ball in alternating possessions. The sport originated in the United States.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>球為橢圓形狀，由兩組各十一人的隊伍在劃有垂直碼線、稱做「烤盤」的長方形球場上進行之運動。由英式橄欖球和足球（英式足球）演化而來；與足球最大的不同處在於，橄欖球球員可以雙手碰觸投擲球、並環抱球移動，與英式橄欖球不同的地方則是，橄欖球可雙方輪流交換球權。發源於美國。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
